Alexander, 1973, male 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">29</emphasis>
terminalia, dorsal view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">30</emphasis>
terminalia, ventral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">31</emphasis>
aedeagal complex, dorsal view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">32</emphasis>
aedeagal complex, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">33</emphasis>
aedeagal complex, ventral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (29-33).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Female</emphasis>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">N</emphasis>
=6): Body length 9.3-13.2 mm, wing length 10.8-12.3 mm, antenna length 1.2-1.4 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Female (Figs 24-27) resembles male. Thoracic pleuron more brownish yellow. Abdomen plump, dark brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Ovipositor (Figs 24-27) short and fleshy, brownish yellow; cercus oval; Hypogynial valve longer.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">. India (Assam); China (Xizang).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Remarks</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="155">. This species was known previously only from India. With the present contribution it is recorded from China for the first time.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
